<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ai-assisted-specification-writing">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>sdd</group>
    <domain>sdd</domain>
    <summary>Collaborative human-AI specification creation using LLMs to draft, refine, and validate requirements before implementation begins.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>specification</tag>
      <tag>sdd</tag>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>ai-assisted</tag>
      <tag>human-in-loop</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AI-Assisted Specification Writing</title>
    <summary>Collaborative human-AI specification creation using LLMs to draft, refine, and validate requirements. The workflow: human provides intent, AI structures questions and drafts FR list with edge cases and Given-When-Then acceptance criteria, human reviews and approves, then implementation begins. Human approval gates are mandatory at every stage.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>AI-generated code quality directly correlates with specification quality. Vague intent produces hallucinated requirements; structured specs with explicit edge cases and acceptance criteria produce accurate implementations. LLMs significantly improve SRS quality when used as an intermediate reasoning step (ACL 2025 research), but human-AI synergy outperforms AI-only: LLMs draft, humans validate domain correctness.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new feature, service, or system where requirements are known informally but not structured</item>
        <item>Producing spec.md and design.md documents in the SDD lifecycle before implementation begins</item>
        <item>When a human has described intent but edge cases, dependencies, and acceptance criteria are not yet explicit</item>
        <item>Reviewing an existing specification for completeness, internal conflicts, and missing acceptance criteria</item>
        <item>Converting informal requirements (meeting notes, chat logs, PRDs) into structured SDD-format specifications</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When domain knowledge is highly specialized (medical, legal, financial regulatory) and the agent lacks sufficient context — garbage-in-garbage-out on domain-specific requirements</item>
        <item>When specifications are already complete and formally approved — agent review adds no value and risks introducing changes to finalized docs</item>
        <item>For pure infrastructure or configuration tasks where the spec is trivially derived from the implementation</item>
        <item>When no human reviewer is available — AI-generated specs must always have a human approval gate before implementation begins</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="limitations">
      <p>AI cannot infer business rules, political constraints, or organizational priorities that were never stated — these require explicit human input.</p>
      <p>Acceptance criteria generated by AI tend to be technically correct but miss subtle UX edge cases and domain-specific business rules.</p>
      <p>Context window limits constrain how much existing codebase context can be included alongside the spec generation prompt — large systems require decomposed, phase-by-phase spec generation.</p>
      <p>Specs generated from vague intent (1-2 sentence descriptions) reliably contain hallucinated requirements that seem plausible but conflict with actual product intent.</p>
      <p>AI cannot validate that requirements are mutually consistent without a dedicated consistency-check pass.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="core-principles">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write specifications before implementation begins — capture expected behaviors, edge cases, and constraints upfront.</statement>
        <rationale>AI-generated code quality directly correlates with specification quality. Vague intent produces hallucinated requirements. A well-specified feature with explicit edge cases and acceptance criteria produces accurate, consistent implementation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require human approval after every AI-generated specification before implementation tasks are created.</statement>
        <rationale>AI lacks domain context, organizational priorities, and business rule nuance. AI-generated specs contain plausible-sounding but incorrect requirements that only a domain expert can identify. Without a human gate, these errors propagate into implementation and compound.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>State non-goals explicitly in every specification — LLMs will generate requirements for topics not excluded.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs attempt to be helpful by inferring what "should" be included. An auth feature spec without an explicit "this spec does not cover password reset" will often contain a password reset FR that was never intended.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep individual spec files under 15,000 tokens — coherence degrades in very long specs even within large context windows.</statement>
        <rationale>Research confirms 150-200 requirement limit per spec call maintains model consistency. Beyond this, LLMs begin contradicting earlier requirements and losing constraint awareness.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="sdd-ai-workflow-phases">
      <list>
        <item>INTENT: human describes problem, constraints, context</item>
        <item>SPEC: AI + human collaboration — AI structures, asks questions, drafts; human validates</item>
        <item>PLAN: AI generates implementation-plan.md from approved spec</item>
        <item>EXECUTION: AI agent executes tasks from plan</item>
        <item>REVIEW: human verifies implementation against acceptance criteria</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="human-ai-collaboration-by-phase">
      <list>
        <item>Intent capture: human describes problem; AI structures thoughts and asks clarifying questions</item>
        <item>Requirement extraction: human validates completeness; AI generates from context</item>
        <item>Edge cases: human confirms business relevance; AI enumerates technical possibilities</item>
        <item>Acceptance criteria: human approves and verifies testability; AI drafts Given-When-Then</item>
        <item>Validation: human final approval; AI checks consistency and completeness</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="supported-specification-formats">
      <list>
        <item>Structured Markdown (spec.md): technical specs, internal docs — default for SDD</item>
        <item>BDD/Gherkin (Given-When-Then): testable criteria, QA alignment</item>
        <item>YAML/JSON: machine-readable specs, OpenAPI, JSON Schema</item>
        <item>Natural language: stakeholder communication, early-stage exploration</item>
        <item>EARS notation: "When [trigger], the [system]..." — formal enterprise requirements</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="llm-selection">
      <list>
        <item>Claude Opus/Sonnet 4.x: complex system specs, long documents, 200k context — default choice</item>
        <item>GPT-4.1/5.x: general specs, polyglot projects, balanced versatility</item>
        <item>Gemini 2.5/3 Pro: massive context (1M+), large-scale projects, codebase analysis</item>
        <item>o1/o3: formal specs, complex dependency chains, advanced reasoning requirements</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A Claude subagent running the SDD specification workflow receives human intent as input, asks structured clarifying questions, then generates spec.md using the standard template (functional requirements in FR-X format, edge cases, acceptance criteria in Given-When-Then, dependencies, out-of-scope items). A second review pass checks for internal conflicts, missing acceptance criteria, and ambiguous language. The output is staged for human approval before any implementation tasks are created. This matches the INTENT → SPEC phase of the SDD-AI workflow where AI drafts and human approves.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>/faion — quality gates for spec review, pattern/mistake memory from prior specs</item>
        <item>brainstorm — diverge-converge ideation for complex system specs with uncertain requirements</item>
        <item>/faion — downstream consumer of approved specs; drives implementation tasks</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="specification-pre-phase">
      <list>
        <item>Define the problem statement: what problem are we solving and why does it matter</item>
        <item>Identify target users and their personas</item>
        <item>List known constraints: technical, business, regulatory, timeline</item>
        <item>Gather existing context: related specs, codebase patterns, past decisions</item>
        <item>Prepare domain terminology the AI needs to understand</item>
        <item>Set scope boundaries: what is explicitly NOT in scope</item>
        <item>Choose appropriate model: Claude for complexity, GPT for versatility, Gemini for scale</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="phase-1-intent-capture">
      <list>
        <item>Describe the feature or system in natural language</item>
        <item>Let AI ask clarifying questions — answer all questions thoroughly</item>
        <item>Identify stakeholders: who cares about this, who approves</item>
        <item>Define success criteria: how do we know when it's done</item>
        <item>Document assumptions: what are we taking for granted</item>
        <item>Review AI's understanding: does it match your mental model</item>
        <item>Correct any misunderstandings explicitly</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="phase-2-requirements-extraction">
      <list>
        <item>Generate functional requirements list (FR-1, FR-2, ... format)</item>
        <item>Verify completeness: ask AI "what functionality might I have missed"</item>
        <item>Prioritize: MoSCoW (must-have vs nice-to-have)</item>
        <item>Check for conflicts: ask AI to identify conflicting requirements</item>
        <item>Generate non-functional requirements: performance, security, scalability, reliability</item>
        <item>Ask AI to enumerate edge cases: "what could go wrong"</item>
        <item>Document error scenarios, boundary conditions, concurrent scenarios</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="phase-3-acceptance-criteria">
      <list>
        <item>Write at least one Given-When-Then criterion per functional requirement</item>
        <item>Include both positive (happy path) and negative (error path) scenarios</item>
        <item>Use concrete data values — not "valid input" but "user@example.com"</item>
        <item>Verify each criterion is independently testable without ambiguity</item>
        <item>Check: no vague terms like "quickly", "efficiently", "properly"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="phase-4-ai-validation-review">
      <list>
        <item>Ask AI to review for missing requirements</item>
        <item>Ask AI to identify conflicting requirements</item>
        <item>Ask AI to flag ambiguous acceptance criteria</item>
        <item>Check: all requirements have acceptance criteria</item>
        <item>Check: all edge cases documented and handled</item>
        <item>Check: non-goals clearly stated</item>
        <item>Check: dependencies explicitly listed</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="phase-5-human-review-and-sign-off">
      <list>
        <item>Verify business logic is correct against actual domain knowledge</item>
        <item>Confirm edge cases are realistic — not over-engineered</item>
        <item>Verify constraints are accurately stated</item>
        <item>Product owner approval: requirements match vision</item>
        <item>Tech lead approval: design is feasible</item>
        <item>QA approval: criteria are testable</item>
        <item>Commit spec to git: version-control every iteration</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="input-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Providing vague 1-2 sentence feature descriptions to the LLM</description>
        <reason>Specs generated from vague intent reliably contain hallucinated requirements that seem plausible but conflict with actual product intent. The LLM fills gaps with the most common interpretation, which may not match yours.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Omitting an explicit out-of-scope section</description>
        <reason>LLMs generate requirements for implied topics. A payment spec without "this spec does not cover refunds or chargebacks" will contain refund and chargeback FRs that were never intended and bloat implementation scope.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Relying on AI for domain-specific business rules</description>
        <reason>AI lacks your specific organizational context, pricing model, regulatory constraints, and product history. Business rules stated implicitly in prompts are misinterpreted; all domain rules must be stated explicitly.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="review-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Accepting AI-generated spec without reviewing every FR</description>
        <reason>AI generates requirements that are technically coherent but businesslogically incorrect. Reviewing only structure and format misses the plausible-sounding-but-wrong requirements that cause incorrect implementation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating AI-generated Given-When-Then criteria as QA-ready without review</description>
        <reason>Agent-generated acceptance criteria frequently test the implementation path rather than the requirement. Criteria must be behavior-focused: "when user submits invalid email, then error message appears" not "when validator.validate() throws, then catch block runs".</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Skipping the dedicated consistency-check pass</description>
        <reason>AI cannot self-assess consistency within a single generation pass. A separate review call with explicit conflict-detection instructions catches contradictions between requirements that are invisible to the original drafting call.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="process-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Combining spec generation and implementation planning in one prompt</description>
        <reason>Mixing both tasks in one prompt degrades quality for both outputs. The planning phase requires the spec to be complete and approved; generating both simultaneously skips the human review gate.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generating a spec and immediately proceeding to implementation without human approval</description>
        <reason>This is the primary cause of wasted implementation work. The agent cannot self-assess whether a spec is good enough for implementation to start — that judgment requires a human with domain context.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Creating specs over 15,000 tokens in a single file</description>
        <reason>LLMs lose coherence in very long specs even within large context windows — they begin contradicting earlier requirements and losing track of stated constraints. Break large systems into 5-6 focused phases of 30-50 requirements each.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Always include an explicit "Out of scope" section — AI will attempt to fulfill implied requirements if scope boundaries are missing</item>
        <item>Break large system specs into 5-6 focused phases of 30-50 requirements each; this stays within model consistency limits</item>
        <item>Provide concrete examples in the input prompt ("like X but different in Y way") — AI generates more accurate requirements from analogies than from abstract descriptions</item>
        <item>After AI generates the spec, run a dedicated consistency-check pass with a separate agent call before human review — catch structural issues before the human reviews</item>
        <item>Version control every spec iteration in git — spec evolution is part of the audit trail and enables tracing requirement changes to code changes</item>
        <item>State non-goals explicitly ("this spec does not cover authentication, billing, or multi-tenancy") — LLMs will generate requirements for these if not excluded</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents generating specs from brief descriptions often invent reasonable-sounding but incorrect business rules — human must review every FR, not just the structure</item>
        <item>Given-When-Then acceptance criteria generated by agents frequently test the implementation path rather than the requirement — humans must verify criteria are behavior-focused, not implementation-focused</item>
        <item>Agents with large context windows (200k) still lose coherence in very long specs — keep individual spec files under 15,000 tokens for consistent output quality</item>
        <item>If an agent generates a spec and then immediately proceeds to implementation planning, it may never surface the clarifying questions that would have caught ambiguity — separate the spec generation call from the plan generation call</item>
        <item>Agents will not proactively flag when they lack domain context; they generate plausible-sounding requirements instead — always prompt explicitly: "List any assumptions you made and any information you are missing"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>markdown-toc: Generate table of contents for long spec documents. Install: npm i -g markdown-toc</item>
        <item>markdownlint: Lint spec.md for formatting consistency. Install: npm i -g markdownlint-cli / https://github.com/DavidAnson/markdownlint</item>
        <item>vale: Prose style checker for spec documents. Docs: https://vale.sh/</item>
        <item>git diff: Track spec evolution across review cycles. System tool</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>AWS Kiro: SaaS IDE with 3-phase Specify→Plan→Execute workflow; spec editor with AI assist. Partial agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Claude Code: OSS/local with long context (200k), direct file read/write for spec.md generation. Yes — native agent support.</item>
        <item>GitHub Copilot Workspace: SaaS spec-driven issue creation; GitHub-integrated spec workflow. Partial agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Cursor: SaaS/local with inline spec editing and AI; composer mode for multi-file spec generation. Partial agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Linear: SaaS issue tracking; agent can create issues from approved spec FR list via API. Partial agent-friendly.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <p>Prompt for initial spec generation with context structure:</p>
      <code lang="xml"><![CDATA[<task>Generate a specification for the following feature.</task>
<context>
  <product>{{product_description}}</product>
  <users>{{user_personas}}</users>
  <constraints>{{technical_and_business_constraints}}</constraints>
  <intent>{{feature_intent}}</intent>
</context>
<requirements>
  1. List functional requirements in FR-X format (FR-1, FR-2, ...)
  2. Identify and document edge cases
  3. Write acceptance criteria in Given-When-Then format for each FR
  4. List dependencies (internal systems, external APIs, data sources)
  5. List explicitly what is OUT OF SCOPE
  6. Flag any assumptions made due to missing information
</requirements>
<format>Use the standard spec.md template from SDD methodology.</format>]]></code>
      <p>Prompt for spec review: completeness, conflicts, testability:</p>
      <code lang="xml"><![CDATA[<task>Review this specification for quality issues.</task>
<spec>{{spec_content}}</spec>
<checks>
  - Internal conflicts between requirements
  - Acceptance criteria missing for any FR
  - Untestable or ambiguous acceptance criteria
  - Missing out-of-scope section
  - Requirements that depend on undefined external systems
</checks>
<output>JSON: { issues: [{fr: "FR-X", type: "conflict|missing|ambiguous", detail: "..."}] }</output>]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="specification-consistency-check-script">
      <p>Bash script to validate spec.md completeness (runs markdownlint + checks for Given-When-Then coverage):</p>
      <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[#!/bin/bash
# check-spec.sh — validate spec.md completeness
SPEC="${1:?Usage: $0 <spec.md>}"

markdownlint "$SPEC" --config .markdownlint.json 2>&1

# Count FR entries
FR_COUNT=$(grep -cP '^- \*\*FR-\d+\*\*' "$SPEC" || grep -c 'FR-[0-9]' "$SPEC" || true)
# Count Given-When-Then blocks
GWT_COUNT=$(grep -c 'Given ' "$SPEC" || true)

echo "Functional requirements: $FR_COUNT"
echo "Given-When-Then blocks: $GWT_COUNT"

if [ "$GWT_COUNT" -lt "$FR_COUNT" ]; then
  echo "WARNING: $((FR_COUNT - GWT_COUNT)) requirements may be missing acceptance criteria"
fi]]></code>
    </section>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://kiro.dev/docs/specs/">AWS Kiro specification-driven development</link>
      <link href="https://addyosmani.com/blog/good-spec/">How to write a good spec for AI agents</link>
